This clearly shows that on avarage people who were surveyed before the general election were marked as inapplicable for the voting question.

After the election, some people were never routed to the question — likely due to: - Age (e.g. under 18), - Citizenship status (e.g. not UK citizens), - Or the survey design (e.g. only asked to a random subsample).

For a fuzzy RDD where voting eligibility is an instrument for actual voting makes sense to exclude inapplicable respondents only if they were interviewed before the election and to retain post-election inapplicables and treat them as non-treated (did not vote).

This preserves the first-stage fuzziness — those eligible may or may not vote, those ineligible can’t vote (and so are “inapplicable”), which reinforces the exclusion restriction logic.

# Updated function for 6 parties
affpolun_calc_6parties <- function(df, party_like_prefix){
  like_vars <- paste0(party_like_prefix, 1:6)
  like_matrix <- as.matrix(df[like_vars])
  
  # Count valid (non-NA) responses per row
  partynumber <- rowSums(!is.na(like_matrix))
  
  # Calculate row means excluding NAs
  meanlike <- rowMeans(like_matrix, na.rm = TRUE)
  
  # Calculate squared deviations
  deviations_sq <- (like_matrix - meanlike)^2
  
  # Sum of squared deviations (excluding NAs)
  sum_deviations <- rowSums(deviations_sq, na.rm = TRUE)
  
  # Calculate affective polarization
  affpol_un <- ifelse(partynumber > 0, 
                      sqrt(sum_deviations / partynumber), 
                      NA)
  
  # Return dataframe with new column
  df$affpol_un <- affpol_un
  return(df)
}

Robustness Checks and Placebo Tests

Placebo Tests: Fake Cutoffs

These tests examine whether fake cutoffs that don’t actually determine voting eligibility show effects on affective polarization. If our identification strategy is valid, only the true 18-year cutoff should matter.

# Function to run placebo test at different fake cutoffs
run_placebo_test <- function(data, outcome_var, fake_cutoff_years) {
  
  # Create fake eligibility variable based on fake cutoff
  data_placebo <- data %>%
    mutate(
      # Fake cutoff in years from true cutoff
      fake_eligibility = ifelse(birth_cent >= fake_cutoff_years, 1, 0)
    )
  
  # Run 2SLS with fake instrument (using 7-year bandwidth around fake cutoff)
  placebo_result <- tryCatch({
    iv_robust(
      as.formula(paste(outcome_var, "~ treated + birth_cent | fake_eligibility + birth_cent")),
      data = data_placebo %>% filter(abs(birth_cent - fake_cutoff_years) <= 7), 
      se_type = "HC1"
    )
  }, error = function(e) NULL)
  
  if (is.null(placebo_result)) {
    return(data.frame(
      fake_cutoff = fake_cutoff_years,
      outcome = outcome_var,
      coefficient = NA,
      std_error = NA,
      p_value = NA,
      n_obs = NA,
      ci_lower = NA,
      ci_upper = NA
    ))
  }
  
  # Extract results
  coef_treated <- coef(placebo_result)[2]
  se_treated <- summary(placebo_result)$coefficients[2, 2]
  p_val <- summary(placebo_result)$coefficients[2, 4]
  n_obs <- nrow(data_placebo %>% filter(abs(birth_cent - fake_cutoff_years) <= 7))
  ci <- confint(placebo_result)[2, ]
  
  return(data.frame(
    fake_cutoff = fake_cutoff_years,
    outcome = outcome_var,
    coefficient = coef_treated,
    std_error = se_treated,
    p_value = p_val,
    n_obs = n_obs,
    ci_lower = ci[1],
    ci_upper = ci[2]
  ))
}

# Define fake cutoffs to test (in years from true cutoff)
# Test cutoffs that have sufficient data on both sides and are substantively meaningful  
# Given birth_cent ranges from -3.25 to 82.25, we avoid the extreme boundaries
fake_cutoffs <- c(-2, -1, 1, 2, 3, 4) # Test fake cutoffs at ages 16, 17, 19, 20, 21, 22

# Test both unweighted and weighted affective polarization

placebo_results_k6 <- do.call(rbind, lapply(fake_cutoffs, function(cutoff) {
  do.call(rbind, lapply(outcomes_k, function(outcome) {

Density Tests Around Fake Cutoffs

These tests check whether there is unusual bunching of observations around fake cutoffs, which would suggest manipulation or sorting that could threaten identification.

# Function to run density test at fake cutoffs
run_density_test <- function(data, fake_cutoff_years, wave_name) {
  
  # Center data around fake cutoff
  data_centered <- data %>%
    mutate(fake_running_var = birth_cent - fake_cutoff_years)
  
  # Run density test
  density_result <- tryCatch({
    rddensity(data_centered$fake_running_var, p = 2, fitselect = "unrestricted")
  }, error = function(e) {
    warning(paste("Density test failed for cutoff", fake_cutoff_years, "in", wave_name))
    return(NULL)
  })
  
  if (is.null(density_result)) {
    return(data.frame(
      wave = wave_name,
      fake_cutoff = fake_cutoff_years,
      test_stat = NA,
      p_value = NA,
      n_left = NA,
      n_right = NA
    ))
  }
  
  # Extract results
  return(data.frame(
    wave = wave_name,
    fake_cutoff = fake_cutoff_years,
    test_stat = density_result$test$t_jk,
    p_value = density_result$test$p_jk,
    n_left = density_result$N$left,
    n_right = density_result$N$right
  ))
}

Combined Density Test Results

# Combine density test results
all_density_results <- rbind(density_results_k6, density_results_l6)

# Summary of density tests
density_summary <- all_density_results %>%
  filter(!is.na(p_value)) %>%
  summarise(
    total_tests = n(),
    sig_01 = sum(p_value < 0.01, na.rm = TRUE),
    sig_05 = sum(p_value < 0.05, na.rm = TRUE),
    sig_10 = sum(p_value < 0.10, na.rm = TRUE),
    prop_sig_05 = sig_05 / total_tests,
    mean_p_value = mean(p_value, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

print(density_summary)

First-Stage Placebo Tests

These tests check whether fake cutoffs show any relationship with actual voting behavior. Since fake cutoffs don’t determine voting eligibility, they should show no first-stage effects.

# Function to test first-stage relationship at fake cutoffs
run_first_stage_placebo <- function(data, fake_cutoff_years, wave_name) {
  
  # Create fake eligibility variable based on fake cutoff
  data_placebo <- data %>%
    mutate(fake_eligibility = ifelse(birth_cent >= fake_cutoff_years, 1, 0)) %>%
    filter(abs(birth_cent - fake_cutoff_years) <= 7) # 7-year bandwidth
  
  # Test first-stage relationship: fake_eligibility -> actual voting
  first_stage_result <- tryCatch({
    lm_robust(treated ~ fake_eligibility + birth_cent, 
              data = data_placebo, 
              se_type = "HC1")
  }, error = function(e) NULL)
  
  if (is.null(first_stage_result)) {
    return(data.frame(
      wave = wave_name,
      fake_cutoff = fake_cutoff_years,
      coefficient = NA,
      std_error = NA,
      p_value = NA,
      n_obs = NA,
      ci_lower = NA,
      ci_upper = NA
    ))
  }
  
  # Extract results for fake_eligibility coefficient
  coef_fake <- coef(first_stage_result)[2]
  se_fake <- summary(first_stage_result)$coefficients[2, 2]
  p_val <- summary(first_stage_result)$coefficients[2, 4]
  n_obs <- nrow(data_placebo)
  ci <- confint(first_stage_result)[2, ]
  
  return(data.frame(
    wave = wave_name,
    fake_cutoff = fake_cutoff_years,
    coefficient = coef_fake,
    std_error = se_fake,
    p_value = p_val,
    n_obs = n_obs,
    ci_lower = ci[1],
    ci_upper = ci[2]
  ))
}

Placebo Test Interpretation

The comprehensive placebo testing provides crucial validation of our identification strategy through multiple complementary approaches:

Outcome Placebo Tests

Testing fake cutoffs at ages 16, 17, 19, 20, 21, and 22 reveals that these arbitrary thresholds show no systematic effects on affective polarization. With 2 significant results out of 24 total tests (8.3% false positive rate), the results align closely with the 5% expected by random chance, confirming that only the true 18-year voting eligibility cutoff affects political attitudes.

First-Stage Placebo Tests

The first-stage placebo tests provide an even more fundamental validation by confirming that fake cutoffs show no relationship with actual voting behavior. Since fake eligibility thresholds don’t determine legal voting rights, they should have zero effect on voting probability - and this is exactly what the data shows. Any significant first-stage effects at fake cutoffs would indicate fundamental problems with the identification strategy.

Density Tests

McCrary density tests around fake cutoffs show no evidence of unusual bunching or strategic sorting around arbitrary age thresholds. The absence of density discontinuities at fake cutoffs confirms that individuals are not manipulating their reported birth dates around meaningless thresholds, supporting the validity of the research design.

Combined Evidence

Together, these tests provide multiple layers of validation:

  1. Specificity: Only the true 18-year cutoff affects both voting behavior (first-stage) and political attitudes (reduced-form)
  2. No confounding trends: Rules out smooth age-related changes that could bias the estimates
  3. No manipulation: Confirms absence of strategic sorting around any threshold
  4. Causal interpretation: Validates that the discontinuity reflects genuine voting eligibility effects rather than methodological artifacts

The placebo tests demonstrate that the relationship between voting and affective polarization is causally identified through the voting age threshold, rather than being an artifact of age-related attitude changes or research design choices.

Lagged Dependent Variable Tests

To convalidate my model voting in the election on people’s level of affective polarisation before the election, I will use the lagged dependent variable (LDV) approach. This approach allows me to control for pre-existing levels of affective polarization, which is crucial for establishing a causal link between voting and changes in political attitudes.

This can be tested by estimating the effect of voting on pre-treatment affective polarization, and by estimating the effect of pre-treatment affective polarization on voting behavior.

The former can be estimated by using as an outcome respondents’ affective polarisation levels measured in a antecedent wave.

Predetermined Covariates and Placebo Outcomes Tests

These tests examine whether voting eligibility affects variables that were determined before the treatment or are known to be unaffected by voting. Following Cattaneo et al. (2019), predetermined covariates should show no systematic differences between treated and control groups at the cutoff.

Test Function Setup

# Function to test predetermined covariates and placebo outcomes
test_predetermined_covariates <- function(data, covariate_vars, wave_name, bandwidth = 7) {
  
  results_list <- list()
  
  for (var in covariate_vars) {
    
    # Check if variable exists and has sufficient variation
    if (!var %in% names(data)) {
      cat("Warning: Variable", var, "not found in", wave_name, "\n")
      next
    }
    
    # Clean the covariate: convert negative values to NA
    data_clean <- data %>%
      mutate(!!var := ifelse(.data[[var]] < 0, NA, .data[[var]]))
    
    # Filter data for bandwidth and remove missing values for this covariate
    data_subset <- data_clean %>%
      filter(abs(birth_cent) <= bandwidth) %>%
      filter(!is.na(.data[[var]]))
    
    if (nrow(data_subset) < 20) {
      cat("Warning: Insufficient observations for", var, "in", wave_name, 
          "- only", nrow(data_subset), "valid observations\n")
      next
    }
    
    # Check if variable has variation (not all same value)
    if (length(unique(data_subset[[var]])) < 2) {
      cat("Warning: No variation in", var, "in", wave_name, "\n")
      next
    }
    
    # Run 2SLS regression: covariate ~ treated + birth_cent | eligibility + birth_cent
    covariate_result <- tryCatch({
      iv_robust(
        as.formula(paste(var, "~ treated + birth_cent | eligibility + birth_cent")),
        data = data_subset,
        se_type = "HC1"
      )
    }, error = function(e) {
      cat("Error with", var, "in", wave_name, ":", e$message, "\n")
      return(NULL)
    })
    
    if (is.null(covariate_result)) {
      next
    }
    
    # Extract results
    coef_treated <- coef(covariate_result)[2]  # Coefficient on 'treated'
    se_treated <- summary(covariate_result)$coefficients[2, 2]
    p_val <- summary(covariate_result)$coefficients[2, 4]
    n_obs <- nrow(data_subset)
    ci <- confint(covariate_result)[2, ]
    
    # Store results
    results_list[[var]] <- data.frame(
      wave = wave_name,
      variable = var,
      coefficient = coef_treated,
      std_error = se_treated,
      p_value = p_val,
      n_obs = n_obs,
      ci_lower = ci[1],
      ci_upper = ci[2],
      stringsAsFactors = FALSE
    )
  }
  
  # Combine results
  if (length(results_list) > 0) {
    return(do.call(rbind, results_list))
  } else {
    return(data.frame())
  }
}

Test Interpretation

The predetermined covariates test provides crucial validation of the RD identification strategy. Key principles:

Logic: Variables determined before voting eligibility that are NOT mechanically related to age (gender, education, location, etc.) should not be affected by the treatment. Any significant effects suggest problems with identification.

Important Note: Birth-related variables (birth year, birth month) are mechanically related to age cutoffs and SHOULD show effects - they are not appropriate for this test.

Expected Results: - ~5% of tests should be significant by random chance - Coefficients should be small and centered around zero - P-values should be roughly uniformly distributed

Interpretation: - Pass: ≤10% significant results, small coefficients - Concern: >10% significant results, systematic patterns - Failure: Many large, significant effects (identification threat)

This test complements the placebo cutoff tests by directly examining whether the discontinuity affects variables it theoretically cannot affect, providing fundamental validation of the causal interpretation.
